  "@type": "Article",
  "dateModified": "2026-03-05",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-05",
  "description": "A first-class function is a function that a language treats as a value: it can be stored in a variable, passed as an argument to another function, and returned as a result from a function. The function itself — not its name or its result — is the value that moves through the program.\nThis property is what makes higher-order functions possible. If functions are not first-class, then map, filter, and reduce cannot exist in their general form, because there is no way to hand a function to another function as an argument.\n",
